The majority of the top rated risks from our DMFEA are related to the jig design. The jig test will be done in three parts: checking the MPHX jig's linearity, making sure the MPHX jig doesn't receive glue from the roller applicator in unintended spots resulting in accidental adhesion, and checking how well the MPHX jig and lamina jig interact.

== The MPHX Jig's Linearity
In order to test the MPHX jig's linearity, the jig will be run through the roller and feed system as normal. This test will be used to check the number of times the MPHX jig catches on the feed and results in a non-working system. The jigs will then be checked and recorded if any obstructions are to occur, specifically checking to see if any spots of the jig catch on the gap in the feed where the roller sits. A table of tests values will be recorded keeping track of how many times the jig catches, the location, and the jig's design specifications (how far the edge of the jig extruded out).

=== The test for linearity:
1. Turn on and set up the roller system (add glue)
2. Place MPHX plates into the MPHX jig
3. Run the system as normal (line up the MPHX jig with the roller system)
4. Wait and check for clear catching of the MPHX jig
5. Record Data
6. Iterate at different angles from directly in line (5-15 degrees)
7. Redesign jig if needed
8. Repeat steps 3-7 as needed



